<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 93 / Motoring: Get a grip on wheelspin
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INCH of snow, or a muddy car park, can bring any car to a wheel-spinning
standstill. A four-wheel drive is the conventional, expensive answer.
A low-cost alternative is a pair of plastic Autotrax ramps, heavily toothed
on both sides to grip both ground and tyre. Slip their thin ends under the
drive wheels, accelerate gently and they will give enough traction to get a
car going. Do not forget to go back for them - they cost about Pounds 30 a
pair and will be in the shops soon. Call 0285-885-201 for details.
Nothing is more difficult to fit into a car than a bicycle. For those
daunted by the thought of lifting cycles on to roof-racks, Paddy Hopkirk has
a universal rear cycle carrier holding up to three bikes.
It can be fitted without tools (and without marking the paint) to almost any
car, but must be used with a number plate or trailer board if the driver is
to stay within the law. About Pounds 50 from motoring shops or call
0525-850-800.
</TEXT>
