<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (27): A capital idea if the cover
looks right - Zero-coupon shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INVESTMENT which pays no income sounds like one for savers to avoid. But
the peculiarities of the British tax system have made zero-coupon preference
shares a much sought-after commodity in recent years. All the return from a
zero comes in the form of capital growth; the share is issued at one price,
and should be repaid at a much greater price in a few years' time.
This profit counts, for tax purposes, as capital gain (unlike the position
on zero coupon bonds, where profits are taxed as income). Since few
investors use up their annual capital gains tax allowance (Pounds 5,800 in
1992-93), the profits are likely to be tax-free.
How do zeros work? They are one class of share within a split-capital
investment trust. A split trust invests in shares in the same way as other
investment trusts, and so repayment of the zero ultimately depends on the
health of the stock market.
However, zeros have first claim on the assets of a trust and are thus
relatively 'safe', although they are still significantly more risky than a
gilt.
The key statistic for judging safety is 'cover'. This measures whether the
current assets of the trust are sufficient to repay the final value of the
zeros. If cover is over 100 per cent, then the trust's assets will need to
fall before there will be any risk to full zero repayment.
You can only really find out the cover level from a stockbroker, which
illustrates how good advice is vital in this area.
Greater risk demands greater reward. So, normally speaking, the 'safer' a
zero, the lower the rate of return. SG Warburg's Private Investor Guide
shows, for example, that at the end of November, the gross redemption yield
on River Plate's zeros (cover 215 per cent) was 7.09 per cent, while the
yield on M&amp;G Recovery zeros (cover 58 per cent) was 11.4 per cent. So when
choosing a zero, the investor has to make a choice between safety and
return.
A second point to consider is the maturity date. You may have some financial
commitment (school fees or a child's wedding) to meet. Zeros can be used as
part of a 'back-to-back' plan with an income-producing security such as a
temporary annuity. The annuity generates a high income; meanwhile, the zero
grows steadily to repay the annuity capital. Taken together, the two
instruments are more tax-efficient than a conventional building society
account would be.
Because of the expansion of the split-capital trust sector in the late
1980s, there is a wealth of maturities on offer. Some will not be paid until
the next millennium; others will mature in 1995.
A third point to remember is that short-term risks are involved. Although
there is an element of certainty about the final redemption value, there are
no guarantees about the day-to-day trading price of a zero.
Zeros behave rather like bonds; their prices rise and fall in inverse
correlation to interest rates. So if interest rates rise, the price of a
zero will normally fall in the short term, as investors sell the zero to buy
better-yielding assets elsewhere.
A sharp fall in the stock market might also cause the price of a zero to
fall, if it raised doubts about the probability that the share would be
repaid in full. Investors should thus regard zeros, like other forms of
shares, as a long-term investment.
One further caveat is needed. There are some split-capital trusts which have
issued zero-coupon debentures; these do not have the same tax advantages as
zero-coupon shares.
For those who find the above factors too complicated, there is a unit trust
which invests specifically in zeros. Exeter's Zero Preference Trust has a
minimum holding of Pounds 750, an initial charge of 5 per cent and an annual
charge of 0.8 per cent.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
