<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (26): Leave it late then beware of
salesmen - Year-end tax planning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE world of personal finance, the year ends on April 5, not December 31.
The end of the tax year is a focal point for financial planning, and can
also provide the financial services industry with an opportunity to
celebrate as wildly as the rest of the population does on New Year's Eve.
When time is running out, the opportunities for high-pressure sales
increase, and most salesmen find this the most profitable time of year.
Many personal tax allowances expire at the end of a tax year, and it is
sensible to leave tax-motivated decisions until late in the year, so that
you have a good idea of how much tax you will be asked to pay. Just make
sure that salesmen do not use tax as an excuse to sell investments which
cannot otherwise be justified.
The main planning opportunities are as follows:
Capital Gains Tax: You are allowed to realise gains of up to Pounds 5,800 in
this tax year, before paying any capital gains tax. This allowance is after
indexation - if your investment does no more than keep track with the retail
prices index, then it will not be deemed to have made any gain for CGT
purposes. Details of the indexation allowance are given each month in the
Weekend FT.
This means that normally only the very wealthy need to pay CGT, and even
they can avoid paying much. The classic method of doing this is 'bed and
breakfasting', the stock exchange nickname for selling shares one afternoon
and buying them back the following morning. This is most sensibly done when
you have already made gains above the Pounds 5,800 post-indexation allowance
in the rest of your portfolio. By establishing a loss elsewhere in the
portfolio, you may still not need to pay CGT for the year.
More speculatively, you can establish a capital gain for the year which is
inside the CGT allowance, while establishing a higher base on which gains
will have to be made for tax to be payable in future. Brokers' fees can eat
into tax savings.
Personal Equity Plans: Pep allowances expire at the end of each tax year.
You are allowed to put up to Pounds 6,000 per year into a general Pep (which
can hold a range of shares, investment or unit trusts investing in UK and
other EC equities), and, more speculatively, another Pounds 3,000 into a
single-company Pep. These investments will then be free of capital gains and
income tax, but you invest out of income which has already been taxed. The
concession is most useful for those who already have a large equity
portfolio, while charges make the benefits more marginal for those who do
not.
Business Expansion Schemes: Like Peps, BES allowances expire at the end of
each tax year (although there are also provisions to carry a limited amount
back if you invest in the following year). BES investments are entitled to
full income tax relief at your top marginal rate, so a 40 per cent taxpayer
investing Pounds 1,000 will receive a rebate of Pounds 400, leaving an
effective post-tax investment of Pounds 600. The maximum annual investment
is Pounds 40,000, so the scheme allows Pounds 16,000 in tax to be reclaimed
each year.
With some exceptions, where banks offer 'non-recourse loans' with only BES
shares as security, these investments must be maintained for five years to
qualify for tax relief.
Pensions and AVCs: These are, again, highly tax-efficient as premiums paid
in to a pension fund are 'grossed up'. But you have to be prepared to wait
until retirement before unlocking your money. Those in personal pension
plans should decide how much money they are prepared to contribute for this
year (the precise funding limits vary with age). Extra contributions can be
made most cost-effectively using single-premium pension contracts.
If you are in a company scheme, you can add to your contributions by putting
money into an additional voluntary contribution (AVC). Total contributions
into the company scheme and the AVC combined must not exceed 15 per cent of
your salary.
Inheritance Tax: Several allowances for IHT are sensitive to the end of the
tax year (see E for Estate planning).
Enterprise Zones: Investment in commercial property on enterprise zones
carries the same incentives as the BES, without any upper limit on annual
investment. But commercial property investment in the current environment is
difficult and speculative. Early this year, there were few opportunities for
EZ investment, although there may be more in future. Wealthy investors
should not ignore this route.
Charities: Top-rate taxpayers with a generous bent might use the Gift Aid
scheme as a way of reclaiming tax. Donations of Pounds 400 or more qualify
for Gift Aid relief. If you give Pounds 400, then it will be treated as net
of basic-rate tax, so the charity can claim tax relief at 25 per cent (an
extra Pounds 133.33). Top-rate payers can then reclaim the 15 per cent
difference between the top and basic rates (Pounds 79.99), meaning that the
charity would have been given Pounds 533.33 for a net outlay of Pounds
320.01.
Much of this is complex, and it is easy to make mistakes. If tax-planning
seems to make sense for you, then it is worth paying for the services of a
good accountant.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6282 Investment Advice.
    P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT931-6874</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DBZCKAHYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930226
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (25): Survive three years to avoid
the net - Expatriates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DONALD ELKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NO ONE knows quite how many voluntary British exiles there are, but the best
guess seems to be something in the order of two millions.
Under Britain's tax code, the closer their connection with the UK, the
greater their exposure to the major direct taxes - income Tax (IT), capital
gains tax (CGT) and inheritance tax (IHT). In determining how close that
connection should be taken to be, three principal statuses need to be
considered: residence, ordinary residence and domicile.
None has a comprehensive statutory definition. Of the three, residence can
most readily be changed; ordinary residence rather less so; while domicile,
which may be defined briefly if not precisely as your natural homeland, is
the most adhesive.
If you were born in the UK of British domiciled parents and have lived
substantially all of your life there, you will be resident, ordinarily
resident and domiciled within the UK and, as such, liable to IT, CGT and IHT
respectively on worldwide income, gains and assets.
Should you spend a complete tax year abroad (ie, April 6 to April 5) without
emigrating or taking up employment, you will become non-resident for the
year but will remain ordinarily resident and domiciled within the UK. As a
result, your overseas income will escape IT for that year, but in all other
respects your worldwide liability will continue.
By contrast, short-term employment overseas which lasts for more than a
year, although without encompassing a complete tax year, will not change any
of the three statuses. Consequently, your UK tax liability will continue
undiminished except, perhaps, in relation to salary itself. For, if you
spend neither 62 consecutive days, nor more in total than one-sixth of the
days in the period in Britain, it will be exempted.
However, if your job overseas does encompass a full tax year, then -
provided it is full-time employment, all the duties of which are performed
outside the UK (incidental duties in the UK can be ignored for this purpose)
and your home visits exceed neither six months in a tax year nor more than
three months on average - you will be treated as not resident and not
ordinarily resident from the day following your departure.
You will then cease to be liable for tax on all income arising outside the
UK and on all capital gains, wherever arising - with the sole exception of
gains from UK business assets. While your liability to IT would continue in
the case of most UK sources - for example, pensions, letting profits and
dividends - there are some exceptions, including income from certain
holdings of British government securities. By contrast, your liability to
IHT would be totally undiminished.
Bear in mind, though, that if your spouse does not also obtain full-time
employment overseas, then if accommodation is retained in the UK for your
joint use, he/she will be UK resident in any year in which a home visit
takes place, thus reintroducing worldwide liability to CGT and, potentially,
IT too.
What then of those who emigrate? They too will, in most cases, be regarded
as not resident and not ordinarily resident from the day after departure,
provided their absence exceeds a complete tax year and UK visits do not
contravene the six-months or three-months average rules. But there are two
important differences. First, if the emigrant is not working then, as for
non-working spouses, residence status in the UK will follow for any year in
which a UK visit takes place, if accommodation available for occupation is
maintained there.
But, most important, emigrants also cease to be domiciled in the countries
that make up the UK. In consequence, their liability to IHT is downgraded to
tax on UK assets only - but not until three years have elapsed from the
change of status.
Thus the UK's domestic law. But in all of these cases, it must be borne in
mind that the rules can be overridden by the provisions of Britain's many
double taxation treaties. They can affect the determination of residence
status and (in the case of the UK/US agreement) domicile, too. The type of
income which can be taxed and the rate applicable may also be varied.
Apart from this, for expatriates to escape totally from the UK's tax net is
not easy. To do so, they must emigrate, have no income arising in the UK,
remove their assets overseas - and then stay alive for three years]
Furthermore, if after your sojourn overseas you return to your homeland, do
not expect any special treatment. Resumption of permanent residence in the
UK brings with it once again taxation on a worldwide basis. For example, the
fact that your assets have been accumulated wholly during your period
overseas will not prevent the Inland Revenue from claiming up to 40 per cent
of them in IHT when you die.
Is this fair? Or has our national familiarity with expatriates bred, if not
contempt, then perhaps a failure to consider the benefits they bring to the
nation?
Donald Elkin is a director of Wilfred T Fry, of Worthing, West Sussex.
</TEXT>
